args: Hey, perfect timing. We were all just\nabout to incite an uprising against\n{player_name}.
You're doing WHAT?! Don't be daft!\nHave you taken leave of your senses?!
My thinker's workin' just fine,\nand we're all ready to tangle.
That you would use honeyed words to\nbewitch His Majesty's comrades and\nfoment an unjust rebellion...
Such wanton villainy must be quelled,\neven if the perpetrator is the leader\nof a Wyrmclan.
What're you gonna do about it, then?
I'll have your head. Right here, right now.
No. As your vassal, he's right to be\nincensed. You could stand to learn a\nlesson about when to be firm.
Or maybe you've yet to truly realize that\nyou're about to lose your precious castle?
What are you trying to do here,\nMitsuhide?

I've got no interest in becoming shogun of
Hinomoto. Defeating all the other leaders
of the Wyrmclans sounds like a hassle and
a half.

So I figure it's way faster to just steal
someone else's kingdom and become the
boss that way. Best of all, I'll have free
rein—or rather, ＂reign＂—to do as I please.
That's why I decided I'd take your castle\nand have your allies fall in line behind me.
No. You'll have neither my friends nor my\ncastle.
I can't stop my friends from leaving me if\nthat's what they wish. I have no right.
But if you think you're going to take things\nfrom me by force, you're in for a rude\nawakening.
Then you're going to fight me and your\nseditious pals?
I can tell from your expression that you're\nwondering how you can resolve this\nwithout bloodshed.
*sigh* I reiterate: you're too soft. But I\nALSO think fighting's a pain, so how about\nwe play a game instead?
A little something I like to call ＂Uprising.＂
I've never heard of any such game.
Naturally, considering I devised it myself.\nThe rules are simple.
Over a period of three days, whichever of\nus acts for someone else first is the loser.
In other words, if you make a slacker like\nme do something for someone else, you\nwin.
Oh, and if we come to a draw,\nI win by default.
Preposterous! You have a massive\nadvantage in a game like that!
Obvi. I made the game, duh.\nSo, are you in?
Are you sure about this, Your Highness?!
If there's a way to solve this without\nfighting, I'm going to do it.
If I've alienated my friends,\nit's because of my own failings.
And that's why I don't want to fight them.\nEven if they ARE rebelling against me.
There's no take-backs on this, you know.
Then the game will begin tomorrow.\nLet's make it a niiice, relaxing,\nenjoyable game of Uprising!
{player_name}, I've confirmed\nthe extent of Mitsuhide's influence.
About half of the people in the castle have\nalready thrown their support behind her.
I beg you not to lose heart, Your Highness.
Yeah...you're right. Sorry. And thank you.\nOkay, let's get the strategy meeting\nstarted.
Is this truly wise? I feel as though we're\nplaying right into the enemy's hands.
This is a battle to protect my comrades.\nTrap or no, I will not turn tail and run.
Understood. Then, I would propose a\ncertain strategy...
The next day, the game of Uprising begins.\n{player_name}'s side makes its move...
All right, let's begin the operation.
Yes. I WILL succeed in rousing Mitsuhide.
Elisanne will call out, and Mitsuhide will\nawaken...
Meaning that we'll be able to assert that\nshe has acted for Elisanne, who wishes for\nher to wake up.
WAKE UP, MITSUHIDE! WAKE UP!\nWAKE UP WAKE UP WAKE UP!
*sigh* Unbelievable. I'm screaming\ndirectly in her ear, and she's not waking...
No, you put up a good fight, Elisanne.\nHer affinity for slumber is fearsome\nindeed.
As long as she's asleep, that gives us\ntime to come up with a Plan B.\nLet's get thinking.
Indeed. We may as well take advantage\nof this opportunity.
How long is she going to sleep for?!
D-don't tell me she's planning to sleep the\nentire day away...
She'll have to wake up and eat eventually.\nLet's go check on her again.
There's a mound on the bed. I guess she's\nsleeping after all?
Did you see that?! Movement! She's—
Mmm, Cleo's bread rolls and cake are\nsublime!
It's important to always build a stockpile\nof food in bed. That way, you don't have\nto budge an inch to chow down!
What?! What kind of sedentary trickery—?!
I can sense her iron will to never leave\nbed. Which is quite the problem...
Yeah. How can we get a person who won't\neven get out of bed to do someone else\na favor?
(Oho ho ho. So naive. You have no idea\nhow firm, how unshakable my resolve is.)
(Struggle, {player_name}.\nI want to see just how far you'll go.)
